# =============================================================================
# .clinerules - LaTeX Specifications Root Directory
# Enterprise AI Platform Documentation Standards
# =============================================================================
# This file defines rules for the LaTeX specifications directory structure
# and ensures consistency across all specification documents.
# =============================================================================

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# DIRECTORY OVERVIEW
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Purpose

This directory contains all LaTeX specification documents for the enterprise
AI platform. Specifications are organized by domain and purpose.

## Directory Structure

| Directory | Type | Description |
|-----------|------|-------------|
| `arabic/` | Use Case | Arabic AP Invoice Processing (Technical) |
| `arabic-hitl/` | Use Case | Arabic AP Invoice (Business Requirements) |
| `tb/` | Use Case | Trial Balance Review (Technical) |
| `tb-hitl/` | Use Case | Trial Balance (Business Requirements) |
| `simula/` | Framework | Training Data Framework |
| `regulations/` | Governance | AI Regulatory Compliance |
| `clinerules-agents/` | Architecture | Agent Swarm Architecture |
| `usecase/` | Grouping | Use case spec grouping directory |

## Shared Files

| File | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `00-executive-summary.tex` | Cross-spec executive summary |
| `00-master-glossary.tex` | Unified glossary |
| `00-cross-spec-dependencies.tex` | Inter-spec dependencies |
| `shared-intent-core.tex` | Shared intent definitions |
| `README.md` | Directory documentation |

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# SPEC CATEGORIES
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Use Case Specifications

Use case specs document specific business process automation:

| Spec | Domain | Schema | Implementation |
|------|--------|--------|----------------|
| arabic/ | AP Invoice | docs/schema/arabic/ | src/intelligence/ocr/ |
| tb/ | Trial Balance | docs/schema/tb/ | src/intelligence/analytics/ |

Each use case has two complementary specifications:
- **Technical Spec** (e.g., `arabic/`) - Implementation guidance
- **Business Requirements** (e.g., `arabic-hitl/`) - Requirements traceability

## Framework Specifications

Framework specs document cross-cutting capabilities:

| Spec | Purpose | Schema |
|------|---------|--------|
| simula/ | Training data generation | docs/schema/simula/ |
| regulations/ | AI compliance | docs/schema/regulations/ |
| clinerules-agents/ | Agent architecture | docs/schema/common/ |

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# SPEC-DRIFT PREVENTION
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Automatic Drift Detection

The spec-drift audit agent monitors all specifications for:
- Schema-spec drift (data model inconsistencies)
- Code-spec drift (implementation divergence)
- Cross-spec drift (inconsistent shared definitions)

## Running Audits

```bash
# Full audit across all specs
make audit-spec-drift

# Audit specific domain
make audit-spec-drift-domain DOMAIN=simula

# Quick check on changed files
make audit-spec-drift-quick
```

## Traceability Registry

All spec-schema-code relationships are documented in:
`docs/schema/spec-code-mapping.yaml`

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# DOCUMENT STANDARDS
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Main Document Structure

Each specification MUST have:
1. **Main .tex file** - Named `<domain>-spec.tex` or `<domain>-<type>-spec.tex`
2. **chapters/ directory** - Numbered chapter files (00-frontmatter.tex, etc.)
3. **.clinerules file** - Domain-specific rules
4. **references.bib** - Bibliography (if needed)

## Chapter Numbering

| Range | Content Type |
|-------|--------------|
| 00 | Front matter, visual aids |
| 01-02 | Introduction, scope |
| 03-05 | Business requirements |
| 06-08 | Design/architecture |
| 09-11 | Data model |
| 12-14 | Implementation |
| 15-16 | Operations |
| 17+ | Future work |
| A1+ | Appendices |

## Citation Standards

All specifications MUST include source traceability:
- Quote source documents verbatim
- Include precise location references
- Document derivation rationale

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# COMPILATION
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Build Commands

```bash
# Compile all specs to PDF
make specs-all

# Compile specific spec
make spec-simula
make spec-arabic
make spec-tb
make spec-regulations
make spec-clinerules-agents

# Export all to DOCX
make specs-docx

# Full export (PDF + DOCX)
make specs-export
```

## Required Tools

- **XeLaTeX** or **LuaLaTeX** - For Unicode (Arabic) support
- **Tectonic** - Alternative LaTeX compiler
- **Pandoc** - For DOCX export

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# ADDING NEW SPECIFICATIONS
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

When adding a new specification:

1. **Create directory structure**
   ```
   docs/latex/specs/<domain>/
   ├── <domain>-spec.tex
   ├── .clinerules
   ├── references.bib
   └── chapters/
       ├── 00-frontmatter.tex
       ├── 01-introduction.tex
       └── ...
   ```

2. **Create schema directory**
   ```
   docs/schema/<domain>/
   └── ...schema.json files...
   ```

3. **Update traceability registry**
   - Add domain to `docs/schema/spec-code-mapping.yaml`
   - Add to `docs/schema/registry.json`

4. **Add Makefile target**
   - Add `spec-<domain>` target to Makefile
   - Add to `specs-all` dependency list

5. **Validate**
   ```bash
   make audit-check-mapping
   make audit-spec-drift-domain DOMAIN=<domain>
   ```

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-SPEC REFERENCES
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Referencing Other Specs

Use consistent labeling for cross-references:

```latex
% In source spec
\label{sec:<domain>-<topic>}

% In referencing spec
See Section~\ref{sec:<domain>-<topic>} in the <Domain> Specification.
```

## Shared Definitions

Shared definitions (enums, types) are in:
- `docs/schema/common/enums.yaml` - Shared enumerations
- `00-master-glossary.tex` - Shared terminology

Changes to shared definitions require RFC approval.

